<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="64" pageId="13" pageNumber="62" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="13" pageNumber="62">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="64" pageId="13" pageNumber="62">
There are two adventive species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Callicerus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Callicerus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Callicerus</taxonomicName>
reported from Canada (
<bibRefCitation author="Brunke, AJ" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="25" pageNumber="74" pagination="119 - 206" title="New species and distributional records of Aleocharinae (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae) from Ontario, Canada, with a checklist of recorded species." url="10.3897/zookeys.186.2947" volume="186" year="2012">Brunke et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
). Males of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Callicerus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Callicerus rigidicornis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rigidicornis">Callicerus rigidicornis</taxonomicName>
do not have their antennomere X conspicuously 
<pageBreakToken pageId="14" pageNumber="63" start="start">elongate</pageBreakToken>
(Fig. 77) as in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Callicerus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Callicerus obscurus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurus">Callicerus obscurus</taxonomicName>
(for illustration, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Brunke, AJ" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="25" pageNumber="74" pagination="119 - 206" title="New species and distributional records of Aleocharinae (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae) from Ontario, Canada, with a checklist of recorded species." url="10.3897/zookeys.186.2947" volume="186" year="2012">Brunke et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Callicerus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Callicerus rigidicornis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rigidicornis">Callicerus rigidicornis</taxonomicName>
may be distinguished externally from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Callicerus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Callicerus obscurus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurus">Callicerus obscurus</taxonomicName>
by the more transverse pronotum (Fig. 77), larger body (length 3.5-5.0 mm), and by body colouration with 
<pageBreakToken pageId="15" pageNumber="64" start="start">lighter</pageBreakToken>
basal half of abdomen (entirely dark brown in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Callicerus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Callicerus obscurus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurus">Callicerus obscurus</taxonomicName>
). The habitus and genital structures of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Callicerus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Callicerus rigidicornis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rigidicornis">Callicerus rigidicornis</taxonomicName>
are illustrated in Figs 77-83. For details of European 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Callicerus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Callicerus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Callicerus</taxonomicName>
species, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Assing, V" journalOrPublisher="Beitraege zur entomologie" pageId="25" pageNumber="74" pagination="247 - 333" title="A revision of Callicerus Gravenhorst 1802, Pseudodemiris Machula 1935, and Sapocallus Sharp 1888." volume="51" year="2001">Assing (2001)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
